{f}ManagementAlert.json.name: ManagementAlert
{f}ManagementAlert.json.description:
When managers set the approve flag on a Conference Offer, this resource provides mapping and transformation for the MQTT message for the Conf Management service.

See the Integration Rules (Alert Management - JSON Message).

{f}PartnerConfirmation.json.name: PartnerConfirmation
{f}PartnerConfirmation.json.description:
When managers set the Approve flag on a Conference Offer, this resource provides mapping and transformation for sending confirmations to Partners.

See the Integration Rules (Alert Management - JSON Message).

This is a good example of Data Integration, based on Multiple Data Sources, with a Virtual Foreign Key across them defined in the Schema screen.

{f}PartnerPost.json.name: PartnerPost
{f}PartnerPost.json.description:
Partners post to this endpoint - the request data represents offers for conference participation. 
This maps incoming requests (note Cost aliased as Price on ExhibitsList) into table rows, and saves these rows onto underlying tables ConferenceOffers, Exhibits and Talks (running any relevant rules).

Posted request data is audited to PartnerPostAudit, per Extended Properties (see tab, above), and Request Event (AuditRequests).

{f}event_alert_api.json.name: event_alert_api
{f}event_alert_api.json.title: Alert Management - API
{f}event_alert_api.json.comments:
APIs are commonly used for integration.  Note, though, that when the target system is down, the post fails, and this transaction would be rolled back.,
making this service less autonomous.  A more autonomous approach is shown in Alert Management - JSON Message

{d}ConferenceOffers.{f}event_alert_api.js: if (row.Approved === true && row.Approved !== oldRow.Approved) {    var payload = logicContext.transformCurrentRow('ManagementAlert');    logicContext.logDebug("Alert Management / API -- posting to: " + ConfigLib.confManagementURL +                            ", auth: " + JSON.stringify(ConfigLib.confManagementAuth) +                            ", request data: " + payload);    var postResponse = SysUtility.restPost(ConfigLib.confManagementURL, null, ConfigLib.confManagementAuth, payload);    if (JSON.parse(postResponse).statusCode !== 201) {        throw "Alert Management / API -- unexpected post response: " + postResponse;    }}

{f}event_alert_apiXML.json.name: event_alert_apiXML
{f}event_alert_apiXML.json.title: Alert Management - XML Message
{f}event_alert_apiXML.json.comments: Same as "Alert Management - JSON Message", changed to illustrate how to format the request as xml instead of JSON

{f}event_alert_json.json.name: event_alert_json
{f}event_alert_json.json.title: Alert Management - JSON Message
{f}event_alert_json.json.comments:
Microservices architecture recommends that systems be autonomous, with decreased dependence on other systems. This internal communication is by way of a message (rather than an API), so that the event system functions even while Management is down.
This event rule type uses an MQTT message;  the same approach would be used for other message brokers.

{d}ConferenceOffers.{f}event_alert_json.js: var title = "ConfOffer Alert: ";if (row.Approved === true && row.Approved !== oldRow.Approved) {    var msgContent = logicContext.transformCurrentRow('ManagementAlert');    var result = false;    try {	    result = SysUtility.publishMessage("PublishManagementConnection","ProcessChargesTopic", msgContent, null);    } catch (e) {        ConfLib.db(title + "exception: " + e, logicContext);        throw e;    }	ConfLib.db(title + "ConfOffer posted to Conference Management listener, result: " + result, logicContext);	msgContent = logicContext.transformCurrentRow('PartnerConfirmation');	if (row.PartnerURL === null) {	    ConfLib.db(title + "No Partner URL, not confirming this back to partner: " + msgContent.substring(1,32) + "...", logicContext);	} else {	    SysUtility.restPost(row.PartnerURL, {}, row.PartnerAuth, msgContent);	}}// built using Examples (Sending Messages) and Control-Space

{f}$0031.$0020Post.json.summary: Logic for default values on PartnerPost.

{d}topics.{f}$0031.$0020Post.html:
As a Marketing Manager, I want to enable our Partners to send us Conference Offers to participate in their events.

Offers provide Options for Talks (Speaking Opportunities), and Exhibits.  These include Costs.

Acceptance Criteria:

  1. Partner can post with this information
  2. Post request data is audited, for admin tracking and error recovery.
  3. Conference Offer data is stored in a local database
  4. A Web App, for users to mark Talks/Exhibits as Used, and approve offers
{d}topics.{f}$0032.$0020Logic.html:
As a Marketing Manager, I need a Web App to denote which Exhibit / Talk to Use.

Acceptance Criteria:

  1. Web App to review Conferences, mark Talks/Exhibits as Used
  2. Verify Cost roll-ups
  3. Verify within Budget
{d}topics.{f}$0033.$0020Integration.html:
As a Marketing Executive, I need a Web App to Approve Conferences, subject to Budget Constraints.  Approvals integrate with Management Systems, and Post a confirmation to the Partner (if they provide a URL).

Acceptance Criteria:

  1. Web App to denote Approved
  2. If ok, forward message (MQTT) to Management
  3. If URL provided, Post Confirmation to Partner
